@article{Carey2015,
abstract = {Estimating raindrop size has been a long-standing objective of polarimetric radar-based precipitation retrieval methods. The relationship between the differential reflectivity Z^sub dr^ and the median volume diameter D^sub 0^ is typically derived empirically using raindrop size distribution observations from a disdrometer, a raindrop physical model, and a radar scattering model. Because disdrometers are known to undersample large raindrops, the maximum drop diameter D^sub max^ is often an assumed parameter in the rain physical model. C-band Z^sub dr^ is sensitive to resonance scattering at drop diameters larger than 5 mm, which falls in the region of uncertainty for D^sub max^. Prior studies have not accounted for resonance scattering at C band and D^sub max^ uncertainty in assessing potential errors in drop size retrievals. As such, a series of experiments are conducted that evaluate the effect of D^sub max^ parameterization on the retrieval error of D^sub 0^ from a fourth-order polynomial function of C-band Z^sub dr^ by varying the assumed D^sub max^ through the range of assumptions found in the literature. Normalized bias errors for estimating D^sub 0^ from C-band Z^sub dr^ range from -8% to 15%, depending on the postulated error in D^sub max^. The absolute normalized bias error increases with C-band Z^sub dr^, can reach 10% for Z^sub dr^ as low as 1-1.75 dB, and can increase from there to values as large as 15%-45% for larger Z^sub dr^, which is a larger potential bias error than is found at S and X band. Uncertainty in D^sub max^ assumptions and the associated potential D^sub 0^ retrieval errors should be noted and accounted for in future C-band polarimetric radar studies.},
